{{Infobox military person | name = Frederick Hambright | image = Frederick Hambright Gravesite.JPG | caption = Frederick Hambright gravesite in Grover, North Carolina. Restoration and maintenance of Col. Hambright's grave and the cemetery where it is located spearheaded by Mr. Ralph Fain Hambright. February 21, 1937-November 10, 2007. | birth_date = 1727 n.s. | death_date = March 9, 1817 (aged 90) | birth_place = [[Moosbach, Germany|Moosbach]], [[Duchy of Bavaria|Bavaria]], [[Holy Roman Empire|HRE]] | death_place = [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], [[Lincoln County, North Carolina|Lincoln County]], [[North Carolina]] | nickname = | allegiance = {{flag|United States|1777}} | branch = Army | serviceyears = 1777-1780 | rank = [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] | unit = *[[North Carolina Line]] of the [[Continental Army]] *Tryon County Militia *Lincoln County Troops (South Fork Boys) | commands = Graham's Regiment of the Tryon County Militia | battles = [[American Revolutionary War]] *[[Battle of Kings Mountain]] | awards = | relations = Spouse(s) # Sarah Hardin # Mary Dover | laterwork = }}
'''Frederick Hambright''' (May 1, 1727 n.s.– March 9, 1817) was a military officer who fought in both the local [[militia]] and in the [[North Carolina Line]] of the [[Continental Army]] during the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]]. He is best known for his participation in the [[Battle of Kings Mountain]] in 1780. Serving as a statesman early in the Revolution, Hambright joined the War in 1777, ranked a [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] in a local militia. His early actions were limited to occasional checks on (and some minor skirmishes with) [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|Loyalist]] groups. This changed in 1780 with Hambright's important role at the Battle of Kings Mountain, which occurred near his lands in the newly formed [[Lincoln County, North Carolina]]. Hambright was commended for his bravery during the battle, though suffering a wound which forced him to permanently resign from military service.
A native of the [[Duchy of Bavaria]], Hambright immigrated to [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]] in 1738. Between 1755 and 1775, he moved several times, first to [[Province of Virginia|Virginia]], and then to various areas in [[North Carolina]]. After the War, he lived the remainder of his life near Kings Mountain.
==Early life== Frederick Hambright was born to Conrad Hambrecht on May 1, 1727 in [[Moosbach, Germany|Moosbach]], Bavaria (then part of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] and in present day [[Germany]]). He lived there for the first eleven years of his life, until the family immigrated to the [[Province of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania Colony]] on October 27, 1738, initially settling in [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania|Lancaster County]]. At the age of eighteen, Hambright left his father's home for [[Henrico County, Virginia|Henrico County]], Virginia. There he married his first wife, Sarah Hardin, sister of Colonel [[Joseph Hardin, Sr.|Joseph Hardin]], who bore him 12 children, 6 of whom were raised to maturity.<ref name="Hunter p. 325">Hunter p. 325</ref> Along with several neighbors, Hambright again emigrated, in 1760, to rural [[Mecklenburg County, North Carolina]] (in the area which was to become [[Tryon County, North Carolina|Tryon County]] in 1768), settling near the [[Catawba River]] close to a frontier fortification that ensured his family's protection from [[Native Americans in the United States|Indian]] attacks.<ref name="Hunter p. 325">Hunter p. 325</ref> This area was to become part of [[Lincoln County, North Carolina]] in 1779, and eventually [[Gaston County, North Carolina|Gaston County]], in 1846.
==Revolutionary War== Before serving as a soldier, Hambright was a signer of the [[Tryon Resolves]] of August 14, 1775, a document which declared that the signers would vow resistance against the [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] for their actions at the [[Battle of Lexington]]. He was a representative of Tryon County, at the [[North Carolina Provincial Congress#Third Provincial Congress|Third Provincial Congress]], which lasted from August 20 to September 10, 1775.<ref>Connor p. 409</ref> In late 1776, Hambright took part in the [[Rutherford Light Horse expedition]] against the [[Overhill Cherokee]].<ref name="Carolina">[http://www.carolana.com/NC/Revolution/revolution_cherokee_expedition_1776.html ''Cherokee Expeditions'']; Carolana.com; retrieved May 2016</ref>
When the war reached Tryon County in 1777, Hambright joined the colonial cause as a lieutenant colonel of the Lincoln County troops, (locally known as "The South Fork Boys"). Hambright was called the "Terror of the [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|Tories]]".<ref name="Hunter p. 326">Hunter p. 326</ref>
===Battle of Kings Mountain=== {{main|Battle of Kings Mountain}}
On May 22, 1780, [[Patrick Ferguson|Major Patrick Ferguson]] was assigned as "Inspector of the British Militia", and was promptly ordered to march to Tryon County, North Carolina to raise troops and to protect the left flank of [[Charles Cornwallis, 1st Marquess Cornwallis|Lord Cornwallis's]] main body which occupied [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] at the time.<ref>Buchanan p. 202</ref><ref>Dameron p. 22</ref> By September 10, Ferguson had established a military camp at Gilbert Town, North Carolina and issued a challenge to the [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriot]] leaders to lay down their arms or he would, "''Lay waste to their country with fire and sword''."<ref>Buchanan p. 208</ref> After receiving this message, Patriot leaders [[Isaac Shelby]] and [[John Sevier]] quickly planned a preemptive campaign against Ferguson's army. They sent messages to military leaders [[William Campbell (general)|William Campbell]] and [[Benjamin Cleveland]] to join them.<ref>Buchanan, pp. 210-211</ref> The rendezvous at [[Sycamore Shoals]] on September 25, brought to Campbell's army 200 Virginians and 160 North Carolinians.<ref>Buchanan p. 213</ref> Another 1,100 "[[Overmountain Men]]," volunteers from the [[Washington District, North Carolina|Washington District]], also arrived to fight for the Patriot cause. The army met with Cleveland's 350 men at [[Burke County, North Carolina]],<ref>Buchanan p. 215</ref> and the now 1,400&ndash;strong force marched towards the [[South Mountains (North Carolina)|South Mountains]].<ref>Buchanan p. 217</ref>
When word of this force reached Ferguson, he sent a message to Cornwallis asking for reinforcements. This message did not reach Cornwallis in time, and on October 1 Ferguson retreated towards the [[Broad River (Carolinas)|Broad River]], asking for local loyalist militia to join him. By October 6, the Patriots had passed Gilbert Town and had reached Cowpens, South Carolina. Local sympathizers informed the Patriots that Ferguson had 1500 men camped on Kings Mountain.<ref name="Buchanan p. 223">Buchanan p. 223</ref>
As they were pressed for time before Ferguson would continue on to Charlotte, Patriot leaders picked 900 men&mdash;including Hambright's&mdash;to ride to Kings Mountain.<ref name="Buchanan p. 223">Buchanan p. 223</ref> By the morning of the 7th, they had reached Kings Mountain, surrounded it, and attacked. The militia's commanding officer, [[William Graham (colonel)|Col. William Graham]], was absent during the battle due to an illness in his family, leaving Hambright in command.<ref name="Hunter p. 326" /> Hambright's group, along with six units, was positioned at the "ball" base beside the "heel" crest of the mountain, in position suited to attack the main Loyalist position. The objective was to catch the Loyalists by surprise. During the assault, Hambright was severely wounded from a musket ball shot to his thigh. Although bleeding badly, he continued fighting. Hambright's comrades were impressed with his bravery, and as fellow soldier, Samuel Moore, later put it: {{quote|"''He knew he was wounded, but was not sick or faint from the loss of blood&mdash; [he] said he could still ride very well, and therefore deemed it his duty to fight on till the battle was over''."<ref name="Hunter p. 326"/>}}
After the battle, Hambright was taken to his nearby log cabin for treatment. He survived, but had to resign from service due to his injury, which caused a permanent limp in Hambright's walk.<ref name="Hunter p. 327">Hunter p. 327</ref>
==Later life== [[File:Hambright Homestead.jpg|thumb|300px|The Hambright Homestead, 1920.]]
After his first wife's death on July 17, 1781, Hambright married Mary Dover. Together they had ten children, eight of whom survived to maturity.<ref name="Hunter p. 327">Hunter p. 327</ref> He lived a quiet life on his homestead near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], until his death on March 9, 1817 at the age of ninety.<ref name="Hunter p. 327">Hunter p. 327</ref> His remains were interred at Old Shiloh Presbyterian Cemetery in [[Grover, North Carolina]].
