'''Michel Gelobter'''  (b. ca 1961)<ref name=NYT2000/> is a [[Social entrepreneurship|social entrepreneur]] especially in the field of [[clean technology]], who is also known for his research into and advocacy for [[environmental justice]].

==Background==
Gelobter grew up in [[Flatbush, Brooklyn]] and on the [[Upper West Side]] of Manhattan. His father was a Polish Jew and his mother was a black Bermudan.<ref name=NYT2000>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Felicia R.|title=Bridging a Divide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/30/nyregion/bridging-a-divide.html|work=The New York Times|date=30 April 2000}}</ref><ref name=NYT2>{{cite news|last1=Schemo|first1=Diana|title=Despite Options on Census Many to Check Black Only|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/02/12/us/despite-options-on-census-many-to-check-black-only.html|work=The New York Times|date=12 February 2000}}</ref>

He earned a B.S. degree in Conservation and Resource Studies in 1984, and then an M.S. and a Ph.D. in 1993, all from the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. His masters' and doctoral research were about economic and racial inequality in the geographical distribution of air pollution.<ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite web|title=Michel Gelobter: Executive Profile & Biography|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=43886902&privcapId=59697298|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=5 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Cole|first1=Luke W.|last2=Foster|first2=Sheila R.|title=From the Ground Up: Environmental Racism and the Rise of the Environmental Justice Movement|date=2001|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9780814715376|page=174|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R6rj8XMSjx4C&pg=174|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Newton|first1=David E.|title=Environmental Justice: A Reference Handbook, 2nd Edition: A Reference Handbook, Second Edition|date=2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781598842241|page=51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y2tFCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA51|language=en}}</ref>

==Career==
After graduating, Gelobter worked for the [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|House of Representatives' Energy and Commerce Committee]], chaired by [[John Dingell]], and then served in the government of the [[New York City|City of New York]] under Mayor [[David Dinkins]] as Director of [[New York City Department of Environmental Protection|Environmental Quality]].<ref name=LeanBio2016/> He then became founding Director of the Environmental Policy Program at [[School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University|Columbia University's School of International and Public Affairs]], where he was appointed an assistant professor.<ref name=Bloomberg/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Michel|first1=Gelobter|title=The Meaning of Urban Environmental Justice|journal=Fordham Urban Law Journal|date=1993|volume=21|issue=3|url=http://ir.lawnet.fordham.edu/ulj/vol21/iss3/19/|language=en}}. See author titles.</ref> Next, he became a professor in the public administration department at [[Rutgers University]].<ref name=NYT2000/><ref name=NYT2007/>

In 2001 he moved back to California and became executive director of an environmental [[think tank]] called Redefining Progress.<ref name=LeanBio2016/><ref name=NYT2007>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Alex|title=Buying Into the Green Movement|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/01/fashion/01green.html|work=The New York Times|date=1 July 2007}}</ref> As part of that organization he advocated for California to adopt strong regulation of [[greenhouse gases]] through [[market mechanism]]s,<ref>{{cite web|title=Redefining Progress Urges Policymakers to Use Market Incentives to Promote Sustainability|url=http://www.planningreport.com/2006/05/17/redefining-progress-urges-policymakers-use-market-incentives-promote-sustainability|publisher=The Planning Report|date=May 17, 2006}}</ref> which contributed to the passing of the [[Global Warming Solutions Act of 2006]].<ref name=LeanBio2016/>

In 2007 he founded Cooler, a [[social venture]] that originally intended to launch a [[carbon offset]] credit card,<ref>{{cite web|last1=American Public Media|title=Green Rush|url=http://americanradioworks.publicradio.org/features/greenrush/a1.html|publisher=American RadioWorks|accessdate=5 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> and then offered two services – one to consumers to provide carbon offsets for goods they bought online, and the other partnering with online retailers to help them source [[carbon neutral]] goods to sell, using a model to calculate the [[carbon footprint]] of the goods.<ref name=LeanBio2016/><ref>{{cite journal|title=How We Calculated CO2 Savings|journal=Backpacker|date=September 2007|page=98|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2vs-RNjRBFUC&pg=PA98|publisher=Active Interest Media, Inc.|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Makower|first1=Joel|title=Cooler and the Quixotic Quest for Carbon-Neutral Consumption|url=https://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2007/10/08/cooler-and-quixotic-quest-carbon-neutral-consumption|work=GreenBiz|date=8 October 2007|language=en}}</ref> He then joined Hara, a [[Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers]]-backed company that developed and sold [[environmental management system]]s, as its Chief Green Officer, and then co-founded BuildingEnergy.com, a [[cloud computing|cloud-based]] building energy management business.<ref name=LeanBio2016/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilner|first1=Tamar|title=Environmental Reporting Pressures Greater than Ever|url=https://www.environmentalleader.com/2011/01/environmental-reporting-pressures-greater-than-ever/|work=Environmental Leader|date=27 January 2011}}</ref>

After that, he started to work with the [[David and Lucile Packard Foundation]] to develop prize-based methods to find solutions to address [[global warming]] in the developing world,<ref name=LeanBio2016/> and joined Infoedge, a [[management consulting]] firm, where he directed their energy practice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Talk Announcement: Michel Gelobter on Presidential Environmentalism from Obama to Trump|url=https://erg.berkeley.edu/event/michel-gelobter-presidential-environmentalism-from-obama-to-trump/|publisher=UCB Energy & Resources Group|accessdate=5 May 2017|date=20 January 2017}}</ref> He is a member of the board of trustees of [[Ceres (organization)|Ceres]].<ref name=CeresProfile>{{cite web|title=Board member profile: Michel Gelobter|url=https://www.ceres.org/about-us/board-directors/michel-gelobter|publisher=Ceres|accessdate=5 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> He served on the board of trustees of the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]], and was a member of the advisory board of [[Al Gore]]'s [[Alliance for Climate Protection]].<ref name=CeresProfile/> He has been a guest speaker at [[Singularity University]],<ref name=SU>{{cite web|title=Guest Speaker Biography: Michel Gelobter|url=https://su.org/faculty-speakers/michel-gelobter/|publisher=Singularity University|accessdate=5 May 2017|language=en}}</ref> and spoke at the 2016 [[The Lean Startup]] Conference.<ref name=LeanBio2016>{{cite web|title=Speaker Bio: Michel Gelobter|url=https://leanstartup.co/2016-conference/speaker/michel-gelobter/|publisher=The Lean Startup 2016 Conference|accessdate=5 May 2017}}</ref> He also lectures at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name=SU/><ref>{{cite web|title=Campus Directory - Michel Gelobter|url=http://www.berkeley.edu/directory/results?search-term=Gelobter|publisher=University of California, Berkeley|accessdate=8 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>

===Advocacy===
Gelobter has urged others to start businesses in the [[clean technology]] sector, in order to create, develop, and validate successful business models. He argues that clean technology companies survive by providing services to companies in the rest of the economy, and if a clean technology company is making money, it does so by helping other kinds of companies make more money as well – in other words, it uses sound environmental practices that are also economically sound and sustainable.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hirsch|first1=Jennifer|title=Three Big Ideas from the Garrison Institute’s Climate, Mind and Behavior Symposium|url=http://www.climateaccess.org/blog/three-big-ideas-garrison|work=Climate Access|date=August 6, 2013|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gelobter|first1=Michel|title=Presentation: Why Making the Road by Walking It Doesn’t Work in Business|url=https://www.garrisoninstitute.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Michel-Gelobter-Why-Making-the-Road-by-Walking-It-Doesn%E2%80%99t-Work-in-Business-CMB-2013.pdf|publisher=The Garrison Institute|date=2013}}</ref>

Gelobter and eight other authors with an [[environmental justice]] perspective responded to the 2005 essay, ''The Death of Environmentalism: Global Warming Politics in a Post-Environmental World,'' by [[Michael Shellenberger]] and [[Ted Nordhaus]] – which asserted that the environmental movement is unable to fully address climate change – with the essay, ''The Soul of Environmentalism: Rediscovering transformational politics in the 21st century''. They argued that Shellenberger and Nordhaus had not addressed the concerns of the non-white poor, and that the environmental movement could be strengthened by allying with [[social justice]] and [[civil rights]] movements.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garofoli|first1=Joe|title=New life through 'Death' / Authors shake up environmentalism with essay on movement's fatal flaws|url=http://www.sfgate.com/politics/joegarofoli/article/EAST-BAY-New-life-through-Death-Authors-2678056.php|work=SFGate|date=April 23, 2005}}</ref><ref name=Cox>{{cite book|last1=Cox|first1=Robert|title=Environmental Communication and the Public Sphere|date=2010|publisher=SAGE|isbn=9781412972116|page=288|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T212jYziosUC&pg=PA288|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Soul2005>{{cite web|last1=Gelobter|first1=Michel|last2=Dorsey|first2=Michael|last3=Fields|first3=Leslie|last4=Goldtooth|first4=Tom|last5=Mendiratta|first5=Anuja|last6=Moore|first6=Richard|last7=Morello-Frosch|first7=Rachel|last8=Shepard|first8=Peggy M.|last9=Torres|first9=Gerald|title=The Soul of Environmentalism Rediscovering transformational politics in the 21st century|url=http://grist.org/comments/soapbox/2005/05/27/gelobter-soul/index1.html|publisher=Grist|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050711000747/http://grist.org/comments/soapbox/2005/05/27/gelobter-soul/index1.html|archivedate=11 July 2005|date=27 May 2005|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>

